        "title":"Uniper trading unit earnings slide 64% amid easing volatility",
        "subtitle":"\n              (Montel) German utility Uniper\u2019s trading arm posted a 64% drop in earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortisation (Ebitda) to EUR 1.5bn in 2024, due to lower gas market volatility, it said on Tuesday.\n            ",
        "body":"\nThe Ebitda of its greener commodities segment \u2013 which includes trading \u2013 dropped to around EUR 1.5bn in 2024, compared with EUR 4.2bn in the previous year, its full-year financial report showed.\nIn 2023, this segment benefited from lower costs to replace lost Russian gas supplies and \u201cunusually high trading results\u201d, it said. However, last year, \u201can altered market environment\u201d prevented it from achieving the previous year\u2019s \u201cexceptionally positive\u201d results.\nSkyrocketing gas prices in 2022 had pushed Uniper to the brink of bankruptcy, as it had to buy gas at elevated price levels to make up for a loss in Russian supply. The German government stepped in with financial aid to rescue the company. \nLower \u201cprice risks\u201dEurope has since offset its Russian gas supply \u2013 which met 40% of EU demand before Moscow\u2019s February 2022 invasion of Ukraine \u2013 with LNG imports, particularly from the US.\nUniper said \u201ccommodity price risks\u201d had since fallen \u201cdue to the reduced volatility\u201d in the market.\nIt said the continent\u2019s benchmark front-month TTF gas contract traded in a range of EUR 30-45\/MWh last year \u2013 down from its record high above EUR 300\/MWh in 2022.\nThe company increased its power hedging activity at the end of December, though its achieved price was down, while it saw full-year earnings for 2024 dive 63%, Montel reported earlier.\n",
